Relaunch restore prompt — implementation reasoning

PROBLEM
The previous startup called restoreSession() unconditionally and, inside
session-persistence.mjs, tried queryPermission/requestPermission({mode:
'readwrite'}) during automatic restore, silently falling back to the
serialized workspace+tab snapshot when handle restore could not complete.
That auto-restore (a) could not reliably grant write permission because
requestPermission needs a transient user activation that an automatic boot
path lacks, and (b) gave the user no choice to start fresh.

CONTRACT CHANGE (session-persistence.mjs)
Split the monolithic restoreSession into:
  - inspectSession(): side-effect-free descriptor used by startup to decide
    whether to prompt. Distinguishes workspace sessions (openTabPaths is an
    array) from source-only (typeof source === 'string').
  - reloadWorkspaceSession(): the explicit reload, MUST run under the prompt
    button click. Returns 'restored' | 'permission-denied' | 'no-session'.
    Denial returns 'permission-denied' (controller re-prompts) instead of the
    old silent snapshot fallback. Snapshot restore (session.workspace) happens
    only here, after an explicit reload, and only when no handle reload worked.
  - restoreSourceSession(): unchanged auto-restore for source-only sessions.
  - clearSession(): clears storage key (set null), handle store, and live fs
    state via fsAPI.resetWorkspace().

ORCHESTRATION (startup-controller.mjs)
runStartup() is DOM-free and fully injected (persistence, showPrompt,
hidePrompt, resetToDefault, enableGate) so it is unit-testable. State machine:
no workspace + source -> restore source + enable gate; no workspace + nothing
-> enable gate (first run); workspace -> show prompt, keep gate disabled until
the user resolves. A `settling` guard prevents double-resolution and, on a
failed reload, resets in finally so the prompt stays retryable.

GESTURE SAFETY
reloadWorkspaceSession awaits loadSession()+handleStore.load() before
requestPermission. Chromium transient activation is time-based (~5s) and
survives sub-millisecond storage reads, so the click gesture remains valid.

TEST STRATEGY / WHY
Existing persistence suite kept (mechanics) but migrated to the new method
names; the denied-permission test was rewritten because the old silent-restore
behavior is exactly what the spec removes. New e2e-session-restore-choice suite
covers the prompt contract end-to-end with fakes: first-run/no-prompt,
source-only auto-restore, prompt shown for workspace, reload restores,
deny->retry, start-new clears storage+handle+fs, dismiss==start-new,
snapshot-only-after-reload, and immediate-persist-after-start-new records the
fresh state rather than the abandoned workspace.

TOOLING
Node UI modules use ESM syntax in .js files; test:e2e passes
--experimental-detect-module so Node < 22.7 imports them. CI now runs test:e2e.
